snippet.textDisplay: It's smaller, more niche titles like this, that 90% of people wouldn't enjoy but are beloved beyond belief by the 10% that are true successes. CoD or Battlefield may sell millions, but I firmly do believe they bring less joy to the people that play them than weird little titles like Deadly Premonition, Killer7 or the Mother series.

snippet.textDisplay: I think that speaks more to your own preferences. Why cannot someone's preferred "niche" be the multiplayer cover-based shooting that CoD or Battlefield offers?
snippet.textOriginal: I think that speaks more to your own preferences. Why cannot someone's preferred "niche" be the multiplayer cover-based shooting that CoD or Battlefield offers?

snippet.textDisplay: @pianoguy222 I don't know, I've always found that niche titles that fit the things I like perfectly are the most enjoyable experiences, simply because they're hitting exactly what they need to hit to make ME, in particular, happy. To put it in RPG terms (because I feel the need to for some reason), they're specializing in the spells I have a weakness to. The way popular titles are spread out to appeal a little to everyone I think isn't as condusive to that kind of stuff. I do enjoy Battlefield a lot (CoD maybe a little less), but I don't enjoy it at quite that fundamental level, if I'm making any sense.

snippet.textDisplay: As someone that enjoys niche titles like Eternal Darkness or Lufia, I don't think it's fair to say they're more fun or bring more joy than the more popular games. Just because it's a different kind of joy, doesn't mean it's lesser.
